04312nam a22006735i 9780292799509DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20211997txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927995097 a10.7560/7119762doi  a(DE-B1597)586736  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aF394.H89bN426 1997eb 7aBIO0020002bisacsh04a305.8/009764/2352201 aCole, Thomas R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aNo Color Is My Kind :bThe Life of Eldrewey Stearns and the Integration of Houston /cThomas R. Cole. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©1997  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPart One. Leader at Last -- t1. Launching a Movement -- t2. Blackout in Houston -- t3. Railroads, Baseball, and the Color Line -- t4. "I Was Going Places" -- tPart Two. A Boy from Galveston and San Augustine -- t5. Uphome -- t6. Rabbit Returns -- t7. Driving Mr. Gus -- tPart Three. Wandering and Return -- t8. "They Got Me, But They Can t Forget Me": A Mad Odyssey -- t9. Drew and Me: Recovering Separate Selves -- tAppendix: Interview Sources -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aNo Color Is My Kind is an uncommon chronicle of identity, fate, and compassion as two men—one Jewish and one African American—set out to rediscover a life lost to manic depression and alcoholism. In 1984, Thomas Cole discovered Eldrewey Stearns in a Galveston psychiatric hospital. Stearns, a fifty-two-year-old black man, complained that although he felt very important, no one understood him. Over the course of the next decade, Cole and Stearns, in a tumultuous and often painful collaboration, recovered Stearns' life before his slide into madness—as a young boy in Galveston and San Augustine and as a civil rights leader and lawyer who sparked Houston's desegregation movement between 1959 and 1963. While other southern cities rocked with violence, Houston integrated its public accommodations peacefully. In these pages appear figures such as Thurgood Marshall, Martin Luther King, Jr., Leon Jaworski, and Dan Rather, all of whom—along with Stearns—maneuvered and conspired to integrate the city quickly and calmly. Weaving the tragic story of a charismatic and deeply troubled leader into the record of a major historic event, Cole also explores his emotionally charged collaboration with Stearns. Their poignant relationship sheds powerful and healing light on contemporary race relations in America, and especially on issues of power, authority, and mental illness.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aAfrican American civil rights workerszTexaszHoustonvBiography. 0aCivil rights movementszTexaszHoustonxHistoryy20th century. 0aCivil rights workerszTexaszHoustonvBiography. 0aMentally illzTexaszHoustonvBiography. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Cultural Heritage.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/71197640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292799509423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292799509/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK